        <dl>
            <dt>World War II</dt>
            <dd class="answer">
                <p>World <img class="du1" src="img/du1.gif"> II (often abbreviated to WWII or WW2), also known as the Second World <img class="du1" src="img/du1.gif"><div id="du1" style="display:none;"> <img src="img/sprite/du1sp.png"></div>, was a <img class="globe" src="img/worldwar1/globe.gif"> <img class="du1" src="img/du1.gif"> that lasted from 1939 to 1945, although related conflicts began earlier. It involved the vast majority of the <img class="du1" src="img/du1.gif">'s countries—including all of the great powers—eventually forming two opposing <img class="army2" src="img/army2.gif"> alliances: the Allies and the Axis. It was the most widespread war in <img class="history" src="img/worldwar1/history.gif">, and directly involved more than 100 million people from over 30 countries. In a state of "total <img class="du1" src="img/du1.gif"> ", the major participants threw their entire economic, <img class="train" src="img/train.gif"> , and <img src="img/computer.gif"> capabilities behind the <img class="du1" src="img/du1.gif"> effort, erasing the distinction between civilian and <img class="army2" src="img/army2.gif"> resources. Marked by mass deaths of civilians, including the Holocaust (in which approximately 11 million people were killed) and the strategic <img class="bomb" src="img/bomb.gif"> of <img class="train" src="img/train.gif"> and population centres (in which approximately one million were killed, and which included the atomic <img class="bomb" src="img/bomb.gif"> of Hiroshima and Nagasaki), it resulted in an estimated 50 million to 85 million <img class="dead" src="img/dead.gif">. These made World <img class="du1" src="img/du1.gif"> II the deadliest conflict in human <img class="history" src="img/worldwar1/history.gif">.</p>
            </dd>
